#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:5
msgid "Usage and Invocations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:11
msgid "Calling pytest through ``python -m pytest``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:15
msgid ""
"You can invoke testing through the Python interpreter from the command line::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:17
msgid "python -m pytest [...]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:19
msgid ""
"This is equivalent to invoking the command line script ``py.test [...]`` "
"directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:23
msgid "Getting help on version, option names, environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:27
msgid ""
"py.test --version   # shows where pytest was imported from\n"
"py.test --fixtures  # show available builtin function arguments\n"
"py.test -h | --help # show help on command line and config file options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:33
msgid "Stopping after the first (or N) failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:35
msgid "To stop the testing process after the first (N) failures::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:37
msgid ""
"py.test -x            # stop after first failure\n"
"py.test --maxfail=2    # stop after two failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:41
msgid "Specifying tests / selecting tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:43
msgid "Several test run options::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:45
msgid ""
"py.test test_mod.py   # run tests in module\n"
"py.test somepath      # run all tests below somepath\n"
"py.test -k stringexpr # only run tests with names that match the\n"
"                      # \"string expression\", e.g. \"MyClass and not "
"method\"\n"
"                      # will select TestMyClass.test_something\n"
"                      # but not TestMyClass.test_method_simple\n"
"py.test test_mod.py::test_func  # only run tests that match the \"node "
"ID\",\n"
"                                # e.g \"test_mod.py::test_func\" will "
"select\n"
"                                # only test_func in test_mod.py\n"
"py.test test_mod.py::TestClass::test_method  # run a single method in\n"
"                                             # a single class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:57
msgid "Import 'pkg' and use its filesystem location to find and run tests::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:59
msgid "py.test --pyargs pkg # run all tests found below directory of pkg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:62
msgid "Modifying Python traceback printing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:64
msgid "Examples for modifying traceback printing::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:66
msgid ""
"py.test --showlocals # show local variables in tracebacks\n"
"py.test -l           # show local variables (shortcut)\n"
"\n"
"py.test --tb=auto    # (default) 'long' tracebacks for the first and last\n"
"                     # entry, but 'short' style for the other entries\n"
"py.test --tb=long    # exhaustive, informative traceback formatting\n"
"py.test --tb=short   # shorter traceback format\n"
"py.test --tb=line    # only one line per failure\n"
"py.test --tb=native  # Python standard library formatting\n"
"py.test --tb=no      # no traceback at all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:77
msgid ""
"The ``--full-trace`` causes very long traces to be printed on error (longer "
"than ``--tb=long``). It also ensures that a stack trace is printed on "
"**KeyboardInterrrupt** (Ctrl+C). This is very useful if the tests are taking "
"too long and you interrupt them with Ctrl+C to find out where the tests are "
"*hanging*. By default no output will be shown (because KeyboardInterrupt is "
"catched by pytest). By using this option you make sure a trace is shown."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:86
msgid "Dropping to PDB_ (Python Debugger) on failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:90
msgid ""
"Python comes with a builtin Python debugger called PDB_.  ``pytest`` allows "
"one to drop into the PDB_ prompt via a command line option::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:93
msgid "py.test --pdb"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:95
msgid ""
"This will invoke the Python debugger on every failure.  Often you might only "
"want to do this for the first failing test to understand a certain failure "
"situation::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:99
msgid ""
"py.test -x --pdb   # drop to PDB on first failure, then end test session\n"
"py.test --pdb --maxfail=3  # drop to PDB for first three failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:102
msgid ""
"Note that on any failure the exception information is stored on ``sys."
"last_value``, ``sys.last_type`` and ``sys.last_traceback``. In interactive "
"use, this allows one to drop into postmortem debugging with any debug tool. "
"One can also manually access the exception information, for example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:108
msgid ""
">>> import sys\n"
">>> sys.last_traceback.tb_lineno\n"
"42\n"
">>> sys.last_value\n"
"AssertionError('assert result == \"ok\"',)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:115
msgid "Setting a breakpoint / aka ``set_trace()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:117
msgid ""
"If you want to set a breakpoint and enter the ``pdb.set_trace()`` you can "
"use a helper::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:120
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ...\n"
"    pytest.set_trace()    # invoke PDB debugger and tracing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:127
msgid ""
"Prior to pytest version 2.0.0 you could only enter PDB_ tracing if you "
"disabled capturing on the command line via ``py.test -s``. In later "
"versions, pytest automatically disables its output capture when you enter "
"PDB_ tracing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:131
msgid "Output capture in other tests is not affected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:132
msgid ""
"Any prior test output that has already been captured and will be processed "
"as such."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:134
msgid ""
"Any later output produced within the same test will not be captured and will "
"instead get sent directly to ``sys.stdout``. Note that this holds true even "
"for test output occurring after you exit the interactive PDB_ tracing "
"session and continue with the regular test run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:141
msgid ""
"Since pytest version 2.4.0 you can also use the native Python ``import pdb;"
"pdb.set_trace()`` call to enter PDB_ tracing without having to use the "
"``pytest.set_trace()`` wrapper or explicitly disable pytest's output "
"capturing via ``py.test -s``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:149
msgid "Profiling test execution duration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:153
msgid "To get a list of the slowest 10 test durations::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:155
msgid "py.test --durations=10"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:159
msgid "Creating JUnitXML format files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:161
msgid ""
"To create result files which can be read by Jenkins_ or other Continuous "
"integration servers, use this invocation::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:164
msgid "py.test --junitxml=path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:166
msgid "to create an XML file at ``path``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:169
msgid "record_xml_property"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:173
msgid ""
"If you want to log additional information for a test, you can use the "
"``record_xml_property`` fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:176
msgid ""
"def test_function(record_xml_property):\n"
"    record_xml_property(\"example_key\", 1)\n"
"    assert 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:182
msgid ""
"This will add an extra property ``example_key=\"1\"`` to the generated "
"``testcase`` tag:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:185
msgid ""
"<testcase classname=\"test_function\" file=\"test_function.py\" line=\"0\" "
"name=\"test_function\" time=\"0.0009\">\n"
"  <properties>\n"
"    <property name=\"example_key\" value=\"1\" />\n"
"  </properties>\n"
"</testcase>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:195
msgid ""
"This is an experimental feature, and its interface might be replaced by "
"something more powerful and general in future versions. The functionality "
"per-se will be kept, however."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:199
msgid "Currently it does not work when used with the ``pytest-xdist`` plugin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:201
msgid ""
"Also please note that using this feature will break any schema verification. "
"This might be a problem when used with some CI servers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:205
msgid "Creating resultlog format files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:207
msgid "To create plain-text machine-readable result files you can issue::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:209
msgid "py.test --resultlog=path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:211
msgid ""
"and look at the content at the ``path`` location.  Such files are used e.g. "
"by the `PyPy-test`_ web page to show test results over several revisions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:218
msgid "Sending test report to online pastebin service"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:220
msgid "**Creating a URL for each test failure**::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:222
msgid "py.test --pastebin=failed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:224
msgid ""
"This will submit test run information to a remote Paste service and provide "
"a URL for each failure.  You may select tests as usual or add for example ``-"
"x`` if you only want to send one particular failure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:228
msgid "**Creating a URL for a whole test session log**::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:230
msgid "py.test --pastebin=all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:232
msgid "Currently only pasting to the http://bpaste.net service is implemented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:235
msgid "Disabling plugins"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:237
msgid ""
"To disable loading specific plugins at invocation time, use the ``-p`` "
"option together with the prefix ``no:``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:240
msgid ""
"Example: to disable loading the plugin ``doctest``, which is responsible for "
"executing doctest tests from text files, invoke py.test like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:243
msgid "py.test -p no:doctest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:248
msgid "Calling pytest from Python code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:252
msgid "You can invoke ``pytest`` from Python code directly::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:254
msgid "pytest.main()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:256
msgid ""
"this acts as if you would call \"py.test\" from the command line. It will "
"not raise ``SystemExit`` but return the exitcode instead. You can pass in "
"options and arguments::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:260
msgid "pytest.main(['-x', 'mytestdir'])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:262
msgid "or pass in a string::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:264
msgid "pytest.main(\"-x mytestdir\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:266
msgid "You can specify additional plugins to ``pytest.main``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:268
msgid ""
"# content of myinvoke.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"class MyPlugin:\n"
"    def pytest_sessionfinish(self):\n"
"        print(\"*** test run reporting finishing\")\n"
"\n"
"pytest.main(\"-qq\", plugins=[MyPlugin()])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:276
msgid ""
"Running it will show that ``MyPlugin`` was added and its hook was invoked::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:279
msgid ""
"$ python myinvoke.py\n"
"*** test run reporting finishing"
msgstr ""
